{{About|the proverb||When in Rome (disambiguation){{!}}When in Rome}}
{{use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}
{{wikt|when in Rome, do as the Romans do}}
{{wikisource|1=Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers: Series I/Volume I/Letters of St. Augustin/Letters of St. Augustin/Chapter 36#Chap. XIV.|2=Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers: Series I}}
{{wikiquote|Rome}}
'''When in Rome, do as the Romans do'''<ref name="Oxford D P">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LMGPCgAAQBAJ | title=Oxford Dictionary of Proverbs | publisher=[[OUP Oxford]] | year=2015 | page=269 | isbn=978-01-910-5959-9 | editor=Speake, Jennifer | edition=6th | oclc=914473236}}</ref> (often shortened to '''when in Rome...''')<ref name="Oxford D WO">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J4i3zV4vnBAC | title=Oxford Dictionary of Word Origins | publisher=OUP Oxford | author=Cresswell, Julia | year=2010 | at=Rome; pp. 371–372 | isbn=978-01-995-4793-7 | oclc=965141221}}</ref> or a later version '''when in Rome, do as the Pope does''',<ref name="Dict IEP">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QBYo_DZRWT8C | title=Dictionary of Idiomatic English Phrases | publisher=[[Thomas Nelson (publisher)#British history|T. Nelson and Sons]] | author=Dixon, James Main | authorlink=James Main Dixon | year=1891 | pages=273 | oclc=156125145}}</ref> a [[proverb]] attributed to [[Saint Ambrose]], means that it is advisable to follow the conventions of the area in which you are residing or visiting.<ref name="Oxford D P" />

[[Saint Monica]] and her son, [[Saint Augustine]], found out that Saturday was observed as a [[fasting|fast day]] in [[Rome#Monarchy, republic, empire|Rome]], where they planned to visit. However, it was not a fast day where they lived in [[Milan]]. They consulted [[Saint Ambrose]] who said "When I am here (in Milan) I do not fast on Saturday, when in Rome I do fast on Saturday." That reply is said to have brought about the saying "When in Rome, do as the Romans do."<ref name="Antiquity of Proverbs">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ttHYAAAAMAAJ | title=The Antiquity of Proverbs: <small>Fifty Familiar Proverbs and Folk Sayings with Annotations and Lists of Connected Forms, Found in All Parts of the World</small> | publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]] | author=Marvin, Dwight Edwards | year=1922 | pages=294–299 | oclc=978104222}}</ref><ref name="D P&F">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6-DQAAAAMAAJ | title=Dictionary of Phrase and Fable: <small>Giving the Derivation, Source, Or Origin of Common Phrases, Allusions, and Words that Have a Tale to Tell</small> | publisher=[[Cassell (publisher)|Cassell]] | author=Brewer, Ebenezer Cobham | authorlink=E. Cobham Brewer | year=1900 | pages=1070 | edition=3 | oclc=258268902}}</ref>

